<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-05-24T09:30:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-05-24T09:30:00-05:00" n="210" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d210">
                                <note rend="inline" type="source">810.20 Defense/19<hi rend="superscript">6/14</hi>: Telegram</note>
                                <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Uruguay</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Wilson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                            State</gloss></hi></head>
                                <opener>
                                    <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Montevideo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-05-24T11:00:00-03:30">May 24, 1940—11 a.m.</date><lb/>[Received May 24—9:50
                                        a.m.]</dateline>
                                </opener>
                                <p>78. Your 39, May 23.<note n="25" xml:id="d210fn1">See footnote
                                        29, <ref target="#pg_16">p. 16</ref>.</note> I saw
                                        Guani<note n="26" xml:id="d210fn2">Alberto Guani, Uruguayan
                                        Minister for Foreign Affairs.</note> last night about this.
                                    He said that personally he favored the suggestion but of course,
                                    would have to consult the President.<note n="27" xml:id="d210fn3">Gen. Alfredo Baldomir.</note> The President
                                    is dining with me tonight and I hope to have an opportunity to
                                    discuss it with him.</p>
                                <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson</hi></signed></closer>
                            </div>
                            </body></text></TEI>